Hi @graphite・43 , we have just merged the mTSP problem into main with the new graphite `__version__ = 1.1.0`. The proportion of the new mTSP problem will gradually increase to 80% of all problems issued over 3 days starting from 0% at block `4138272` ~ Sunday, October 27, 2024 7:00 PM. The remaining portion of problems will remain as large instance TSPs (GraphProblemV2).

There are a few key updates:

For Validators:
1. Merged `presync_weights` branch which alleviates the wild fluctuations in trust that happens when validator neurons stop. The new validators initiate its own weights based on the current metagraph weights then begin validating process and scoring neurons accordingly.

2. ScoreResponse class now supports two scoring functions to handle minmax mTSP solutions (GraphProblemV2Multi) and large instance TSP (GraphProblemV2).

3. The benchmark solution for mTSP is a post-processed version of the Nearest Neighbour heuristic to make it appropriate for minmax mTSP. Solver defined in `graphite/solvers/greedy_solver_multi.py`.

For Miners:
1. To answer the new mTSP, `neurons/miner.py` runs 3 simple heuristics and selects the best solution for submission. These heuristics serve as basic ideas to build more complex algorithms on. Solvers can be found at `graphite/solvers/insertion_solver_multi.py`, `graphite/solvers/greedy_solver_multi.py`, and `graphite/solvers/greedy_solver_multi2.py`.

2. New `tests/evaluate_solvers_multi.py` for mTSP problems.

Notes:
`GraphProblemV2Multi` inherits from `GraphProblemV2`. As such, when doing instance checks, `isinstance(mtsp, GraphProblemV2)` evaluates to `True` and `isinstance(tsp, GraphProblemV2Multi` evaluates to `False`. Please be careful when programming your conditional checks.

Once you get more familiar with working with the data, you can use the data of the past problems posted by validators here:
https://huggingface.co/datasets/Graphite-AI/Graphite_Past_Problems

You can also run the `sync_past_data.py` from this repository: https://github.com/GraphiteAI/subnet_tools which will download all the past data files for you.

The best way to test if your code is better is to construct a problem from the past data and compare the distance results you get against the top results on the subnet.

2. A validator pose questions every 5 mins to 30/240+ miners => i.e 1 miner receives a question every 40 mins

You may now be wondering why we don't make validator pose questions more often to miners. There are 2 reasons:
1. With 11 validators on our subnet, we want to reduce the chances of collision where 2 validators pose a problem at the same time to 1 miner. This may affect their response quality to the validators which can cause unstable vtrust among validators.

Thanks for your detailed explanation, however, rather than experimenting with parameters repeatedly, I believe carefully examining the actual logic in the code might reveal the cause of the fluctuation more directly. Specifically, the current implementation of scattered_rewards treats unselected miners as receiving zero points. Even though miner selection is random (and thus fair), over several dozen rounds, some miners inevitably get selected far more frequently than others, causing significant fluctuations in rewards. (I can demonstrate this with a simple simulation if needed.)

If, instead, the last recorded score was carried forward when a miner isn't selected, volatility would be greatly reduced. I fully agree a reasonable rule should ensure all miners start from a fair baseline and keep volatility minimal.

Regarding your point that "1 miner receives a question every 40 mins" with a 16-hour immunity period, each miner can only expect about 24 questions from a single validator. Even if a miner received a perfect score of 1 for each question, with the current extremely low alpha (0.00001), the resulting score would still be lower than 0.00024. This clearly can't be a reasonable setting.

I understand it's quite challenging to satisfy both of these conditions simultaneously, and I realize there's inevitably a trade-off involved. A more reasonable setup I envision would look like this: Adjust the immunity period to 3 days, and calculate each miner's score based on the average score from the most recent 3 days. This way, each miner's score would reflect an average over approximately 100 questions, significantly reducing fluctuations.

Unselected miners are not given 0 points, they are just not factored into the score update. If you look into our miner selection code, the miners are selected randomly but they are all selected at least once for each epoch. This was already carefully implemented earlier on to reduce fluctuation in rewards. 🙂
